Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current major coalition, as well as a notable strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly large losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthie Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphal return to the political scene at national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 per cent of the votes, the country's first political force, however, compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 per cent of the votes.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 per cent loses nearly nine per cent of the votes, ended up even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major parties in the post-war period; especially for the popular party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Again at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the Popular Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
However, voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer were pronounced.
Observers believe that this could happen on Monday, at the extraordinary meeting of the party leadership.
Such an evolution would a priori facilitate the way towards the outcome of the election outcome, which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the great SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
Nevertheless, in view of the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the free (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 per cent and BZÖ 11 per cent of the votes - the socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the popular party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ separated from it) on a common government, which even raised sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently relies on this evolution.
The last party to have access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell back among the Austrian political parties from the third in fifth place.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four per cent limit and did not accede to parliament.
